5813 Church Ave., at the N.E. corner of Kings Highway, showing the Richard Remsen House, built in 1844 and known then as No. 1 Remsen Place. The house has since been shingled and remodelled; owned by a Mr. Bron, in 1922.

1922.

(2)
The same; seen east of Kings Highway.

March 1923.

text:
5741 King's Highway, east side, between Church and Snyder Aves., showing the John Remsen farmhouse, known also as the Peter Remsen house. This house was built in 1797 by Johannes Remsen. The rear entrance was erected about 1865.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

The same, a year later.

1923.

The same, showing also a partial view of two other homes.

March 1923.

May 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Church Avenue & Kings Highway, Brooklyn, NY
text:
(1) 5813 Church Ave., at the N.E. corner of King's Highway, showing the Richard Remsen house. 1923. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, showing the west side, which faces on King's Highway. This house was erected in 1844. March 1925. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3) The same, looking southward, and showing the opposite side and rear of the house. March 1925. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(4) The same, showing also a view east on Church Ave., and a Church Ave. trolley car. August 7, 1931. P. L. Sperr.

text:
(1)
5735-5749 King's Highway, east side, between Church and Snyder Aves; showing an eastward view across East 57th Street. The one story stucco building at the right, does not appear in the 1929 Atlas. The center house in this view was known as the John Remsen farmhouse. No. 5735 is at the extreme right, partially seen.
March 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, a closeup.
September 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3)
The same, looking northward along the newly laid out King's Highway.
September 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(4)
The same, another angle.
May 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
